nd, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","Malton, Yorkshire, England":"Malton, Yorkshire, England","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Alnwick Castle, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Alnwick Castle, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Malton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Malton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tyson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Dyson</b> (see   Dye  ).","English: nickname from Old French <i>tison</i> ‘firebrand’, perhaps for someone with a fiery temperament.","Americanized form of German   Theissen   or   Theisen  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dye","meanings":["English (Norfolk): from the Middle English female personal name <i>Dye</i>, a pet form of <i>Denis(e)</i> (from Latin <i>Dionisia</i>); see   Dennis  ."]}]},{"name":"Ada","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of uncertain origin; it was not in general use before the late 18th century. It may be a Latinate variant of the biblical name   Adah .  However, it has also been explained as a pet form of   Adele   and   Adelaide  , Germanic female names of which the first element is <i>adal</i> ‘noble’. It was borne by a 7th-century abbess of Saint-Julien-des-Prés at Le Mans."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":3,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":23,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":33,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":43,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Ada Tyson was born in 1063, in Alnwick, Northumberland, England as the daughter of William de Tyson Lord of Alnwick. She married Ivo de Vesci, Lord of Alnwick in 1086, in York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1120, in Malton, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1063–1120":"1063–1120","1065–1157":"1065–1157","1094–1123":"1094–1123","1050–1096":"1050–1096","1066":"1066","1120":"1120","1065":"1065","1086":"1086","1063":"1063","1096":"1096","1094":"1094","1050":"1050","1106":"1106","1157":"1157","1123":"1123","about 1064":"umbes 1064","Abt. 1075":"umbes 1075","Alnwick, Northumberland, England":"Alnwick, Northumberland, England","Malton, Yorkshire, England":"Malton, Yorkshire, England","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, U